latestPosts.caption:
I didn’t plan to post this.
But today was one of those Sundays that made me rethink what ROI really means.

After almost a decade in marketing — building strategies, launching brands, hitting targets — I found myself asking last year:

What will I actually be proud of, when I look back?

A viral reel? A weekend campaign that drove 3x footfall?
Sure, those wins are real. But were they enough for me?

Because here’s the truth no one likes to say out loud:
Not everything we market needs to be sold harder.
And not everything that needs to be seen has a budget.

I wasn’t burnt out. I just wanted my work to mean more.

Now, I work with Saamarthya Foundation as their Social Impact & Communications Manager.
This Sunday, we hosted a Resource Fair for families of neurodivergent children — a space where they could walk in and access free consultations with doctors, therapists, special educators, psychologists, and financial planners.

No charges. No chaos. No red tape.

And almost 60% of the families who came in were new.
They found us through a WhatsApp forward. A referral. A shared Instagram post. A tiny Facebook ad we ran with a limited budget.

No media agency. No paid influencer strategy.
Just trust. Just community. Just relevance.

And that’s when it hit me —
This is ROI too.
Not the kind that shows up on a dashboard.
The kind that shows up in someone’s life.

A mother looked at us and said:
“I didn’t even know support like this existed.”
And honestly, that was it.
That’s the moment that made the whole day worth it.

This wasn’t a glamorous Sunday. But it was real.
And I’d take that kind of work — the kind that moves people, not just numbers —
over a viral campaign, any day.

latestPosts.caption:
I’m usually open to all colours… but the moment I opened this saree from @taani_bani , I knew this one was different.
A rich, striking purple with a clean diamond border.. minimal, classic, and still a head-turner.
It’s called Rajmohini Sharvani: a handwoven Maheshwari saree in a soft cotton-silk blend.

But honestly, it’s not just the saree that drew me in .. it’s the story behind it.
Taani Bani is a mother-daughter-led brand, deeply rooted in Maheshwar’s handloom heritage.
Rutvi’s grandfather was a weaving master who worked across MP’s handloom clusters for decades, from Bhopal to Chanderi and spent years with Rehwa Society, training artisans and preserving the Maheshwari craft.

Years later, Rutvi’s mother picked up the pieces of a dream that had been paused. She started from home, reconnecting with people who had once worked with her father.
Rutvi joined in, bringing her own perspective and love for design into the mix. And together, they built something real , quiet, honest, and full of intention.

And that’s what I personally look for when I choose to collaborate.
Brands that carry stories.
That value process over quick trends.
That choose craft over convenience.

In a world of power looms, synthetic fabrics, and fast fashion, handloom stands out. Not just for how it looks but for what it represents.
It’s slower, yes. But it’s also more thoughtful. More human. And that, to me, makes all the difference.

[maheshwari silk, Maheshwari sarees, Indian textiles, love for sarees, silk sarees, brand stories, sarees, Indian fabric]

Mentally here 🏔️

Took this trip last year and realised how unfit I’d become. I struggled on a beginner-level hike.
For someone who hiked 7–8 times a year in her early 20s, this was a proper wake-up call.

Since then, staying active and eating better has been less about weight and more about getting back to doing the things I love, without struggling.

I’m not an adrenaline junkie. But I’ve always loved a good hike .. for the views, the silence, the peace you feel on the trail.
That high you get when you finally reach the top ..that’s what I miss.

That’s the goal.

latestPosts.caption:
Today marks the 300th birth anniversary of Punyashlok Devi Ahilyabai Holkar. The woman behind the gorgeous Maheshwari Sarees. I’m wearing one from @taani_bani today.

We read about Ahilyabai Holkar in school.
A paragraph in a textbook. A few lines we wrote in an exam.

“Ahilyabai Holkar – Queen of the Holkar dynasty. Known for her wisdom and temple-building.”
That was it.

But you grow up…
And suddenly, you start to see these women for who they really were.
Women who governed with grace, built without ego, and led in a world that wasn’t designed for them to lead.

Ahilyabai was widowed at 29. She had no formal education.
Yet she went on to rule Malwa for decades with such clarity that even the British couldn’t fault her policies.
She brought weavers to Maheshwar, built hundreds of temples across India, and made art and administration part of the same ecosystem.

She wasn’t a ruler because she wanted power.
She ruled because she saw work that needed to be done, and she did it.

The Maheshwari saree is just one part of her legacy.
Not loud. Not ornamental. Just precise, dignified, and deeply rooted, like her.

Wearing this saree from Taani Bani today felt different.
Like a reminder of how much women have always done .. even when history gave them only a footnote.

On her birth anniversary, I hope we remember her not just as a queen…
But as a woman who chose purpose, when the world expected silence.

[Indian textiles, Indian handloom, ahilyabai holkar, textile history, Maheshwari silk sarees, silk sarees]

latestPosts.caption:
A day out with The Volume Company.. but let’s be honest, the work never really stops.
She’s the founder .. handling inventory calls between sips of coffee, checking on packaging while trying to explain scalp health in the simplest words possible. I’m the one behind the camera, capturing the chaos, the calm, and everything in between.

We weren’t at a boardroom. We were at a café with good light, a list of reels to shoot, and a lot of unfiltered conversation about what it really takes to build a brand that’s plant-based, people-first, and painfully honest.

It’s not glossy. It’s not always glamorous.
But it’s real. And sometimes, that’s more than enough.

latestPosts.caption:
A little sunshine to the otherwise cloudy and chaotic times. Meet Coffee ☕️ 

I’ve always had immense respect for people who rescue animals or run shelters. But after caring for an orphaned kitten myself, that respect has turned into something deeper..
Because nothing prepares you for the responsibility of a voiceless little life that has been left all alone, far too early.
The last few weeks have been an emotional rollercoaster. But this little one…
This tiny, fragile soul has taken me on a ride of its own filled with sleepless nights, moments of pure panic, quiet wins, and a whole lot of heart.

It’s beautiful. It’s overwhelming. It’s exhausting. And it’s worth it.
If you’ve ever cared for an animal in need, you’ll know exactly what I mean.
April has been chaotic, messy but memorable 🌻
